1 Background

Water is the cornerstone of First Foods production and inherently tied to the five fundamental touchstones: hydrology, geomorphology, habitat and network connectivity, riverine biotic community, and riparian vegetation (Jones et al. 2008). These touchstones form the Umatilla River Vision, a holistic approach to water quality restoration. To support the Vision, population status and habitat use of riverine fishes defined as First Foods (including Endangered Species Act [ESA] listed middle Columbia River summer-run steelhead, spring-run Chinook salmon, bull trout, and Pacific lamprey) have been identified as critical data needs in the assessment of biotic communities (Jones et al. 2008). The decline of anadromous Pacific salmonid populations (Oncorhynchus spp.) across the Pacific Northwest, USA, has prompted numerous actions aimed at reversing that trend. These actions are often categorized into four â€˜Hâ€™sâ€™ - harvest modification, habitat rehabilitation, hydroelectric operations, and hatchery practices. While there is substantial evidence linking these actions to salmonid survival, complexities regarding responses in population-level productivity result in significant uncertainty when predicting population response and what combination of changes might most cost-effectively and sustainably recover depleted populations. Recovery plans (e.g., NOAA (2009)) have identified adult escapement targets at the population scale, providing a quantitative metric useful for evaluating the magnitude of survival improvements required. These abundance targets provide a benchmark against which habitat rehabilitation actions can be measured. Here, we apply a novel approach to estimating life-stage specific habitat capacity for spring-run Chinook salmon (hereafter Chinook salmon) and summer-run steelhead (hereafter steelhead) to quantify the magnitude and types of tributary habitat restoration needed to achieve recovery goals in the Upper Walla Walla watershed.

We define habitat carrying capacity as the maximal abundance or load the stream habitat can support for a given species and life-stage given current physical habitat quantity and quality. Within fisheries research and management, it has long been recognized that biotic and abiotic factors limit productivity within and across life-stages. However, we assume that observed fish density is a poor predictor of habitat capacity owing to both a paucity of individuals (e.g., low escapement levels) and the existence of unmeasured biotic or abiotic variables that may limit capacity. To address this, we have developed an approach to estimate the carrying capacity of wadable streams to support spawning and rearing Chinook slamon and steelhead using the quantile random forest model (QRF; Meinshausen (2006); Cade and Noon (2003); Idaho OSC Team (2019) - Appendix B) described in See et al. (2021).

2 Methods

2.1 Focal Species

The focal species for the QRF habitat capacity assessment are:

  • Spring-run Chinook salmon (Oncorhynchus tshawytscha; hereafter Chinook salmon)
  • Middle Columbia River summer steelhead (O. mykiss; hereafter steelhead; ESA-listed threatened)

While our habitat capacity models specifically address Chinook salmon and steelhead, any uplift in habitat for these species are also expected to uplift:

  • Columbia River bull trout (Salvelinus confluentus; ESA-listed threatened)
  • Pacific lamprey (Lampetra tridentata)

2.2 Study Area

This assessment will be focused on the alluvial channel of the Walla Walla River from the confluence with Dry Creek near Lowden, Washington, to the headwaters of the North and South forks of the Walla Walla River. The primary study area includes approximately 70 miles of stream.

2.3 Approach Overview

Habitat data from the Columbia Habitat Monitoring Program (CHaMP) were paired to fish survey data to develop fish-habitat relationships (See et al. 2021). Importantly, the QRF model places no assumptions on possible fish-habitat relationships; instead, relationships are estimated from the empirical data regardless of being positive, negative, linear, non-linear, etc. Using the observed fish-habitat relationships, we can predict habitat capacity at any location with habitat data for all model covariates (e.g., at all CHaMP sites). Capacity predictions from these locations can then be used to extrapolate capacity across larger spatial scales using globally available attribute data. Here, we use globally available attribute data for the Upper Walla Walla River to calculate capacity at the watershed scale. Additionally, we apply a generalized capacity model to estimate life-stage specific capacity requirements to achieve given recovery goals. Habitat capacity deficits can then be estimated to determine the amount of additional capacity required to meet recovery goals and used to identify potential limitations by species and life-stage. Finally, we leverage a NorWeST summer stream temperature model (Isaak et al. 2012; Peterson et al. 2013; Isaak et al. 2017) to evaluate changes in predicted capacity for target species and life-stages given various climate scenarios.

2.4 Required Capacity

Life-stage specific capacity requirements were estimated using a Generalized Capacity model with a combination of empirical and literature-based parameter estimates (Table 2.1) to determine capacity necessary to achieve a given recovery goal. A detailed description of the Generalized Capacity model (including other methods considered to estimate capacity requirements) is provided in Appendix C of Idaho OSC Team (2019). We used adult escapement goals of 3,000 for Chinook salmon and 3,400 for steelhead. Briefly, the adult escapement goals are multiplied step-wise by parameter values in Table 2.1 to determine the abundance for a given life-stage necessary to support that goal. For example, the number of redds necessary for recovery is calculated by multiplying the adult escapement goal by an estimate of the proportion of females in the population. Sources for each of the parameter estimates are provided in Table 2.1; however, those values can be modified if more up-to-date or local estimates are available.

Table 2.1: Life history parameters for the generalized capacity model.
Species Parameter Value Source
Chinook Female Ratio 0.49 IDFG/ISEMP
Chinook Redds/Female 1 Bjornn (1978)
Chinook Fecundity 5,290 Snider et al.Â (2005)

2.5 Available Capacity

Capacity estimates were generated following the quantile random forest (QRF) framework outlined in See et al. (2021). The method involves fitting a QRF model paired fish and habitat data across hundreds of sites in seven watersheds within the Columbia River Basin. With that model, we predicted fish density at all sites with associated detailed habitat data. The QRF model produces a distribution of predictions, one for each tree in the forest, and we chose the 90th quantile of that distribution as a proxy for carrying capacity.

2.5.1 Extrapolation

Although we have hundreds of sites across the Columbia River basin with detailed habitat data that were used to estimate capacity with the QRF model, this only covers a small percentage of the anadromous zone within each watershed. Additionally, many watersheds do not contain sites with detailed habitat data. Therefore, we extrapolated our capacity predictions to the areas between these sites using a stream layer available from NOAA fisheries. This layer consists of a polyline shapefile divided into 200m reaches with various attributes attached to each reach. We refer to these as globally available attributes (GAAs) because they are associated with every reach across all watersheds in the Columbia River Basin. The shapefile is based on the National Hydrography Dataset High Resolution (NHDPlus HR) dataset, which has a high resolution, 1:24,000.

We estimated capacity in the Upper Walla Walla River by quantifying the relationships between GAAs and QRF capacity predictions at all of the sites used to populate the QRF model. This was conducted using a second random forest model, with GAAs as covariates and QRF-predicted densites as the response. The random forest approach allows for non-linear associations between capacity and GAAs, and constricts capacity predictions within the predicted range from the initial QRF model. Density predictions for the Upper Walla Walla River watershed are calculated for 200m segments within reaches using the random forest model with GAA inputs, and reach-level capacity is calculated by multiplying the predicted fish/m by the length of that reach. Capacity for specific regions are then calculated by summing capacities for all reaches within the region.
